@Binchan: It is not just about hard core censorship resistance. With an official debian package, ZeroNet could also be much easier to use than any centralized system. No need to decide between insecure passwords or a secure one and stick it to the monitor ;-) 
My mother in law actually runs Ubuntu on her notebook. I might get her to install stuff that is in the software center, anything else is out of the question.
Oh, Religion is a difficult topic. It has its merits in bringing people together, sure. But it is more often misused as a political instrument of power.

@Binchan: Censorship resistance sounds so dramatic as only useful for politically oppressed dissidents. But it is also helpful in small scale. For example there are countless stories about people whose accounts on centralized platforms were blocked or deleted on bogus reasons.
Yes there is also a part that slightly worries me about ZN and similar platforms. There is always a small risk that unwanted content could end up on your hard drive. So everybody should more or less carefully decide what to follow. It is for grown up people.
I don't know yet when I will introduce my kids to this world. Not sure yet which risks for them will weight more..

